{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642463"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:40:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17945"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17945"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.41,0.09,0.14,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78772"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10659"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17945"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64121"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6871"},{"type":"tags","id":"7243"},{"type":"tags","id":"7253"},{"type":"tags","id":"7254"},{"type":"tags","id":"11236"},{"type":"tags","id":"11237"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24836"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78772"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bones of the viscerocranium is not a paired bone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maxilla","Mandible","Zygomatic","Lacrimal","Palatine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emandible\u003C/strong\u003E is a single midline bone in the viscerocranium, unlike most other bones in this region, which are paired. The mandible forms the lower jaw and is crucial for mastication and articulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaxilla\u003C/strong\u003E is a paired bone that forms the upper jaw and part of the orbit. It is involved in the formation of the walls of the orbit, floor of the nose and hard palate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezygomatic\u003C/strong\u003E bones are paired and form part of the floor and lateral wall of the orbit, and the prominence of the cheeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elacrimal\u003C/strong\u003E bones are paired bones that are located in the medial wall of the orbit, and are the smallest and most fragile bones of the face. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalatine\u003C/strong\u003E bones are paired and form part of the hard palate, the floor of the nose, and the floor of the orbit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mandible is a single midline bone in the viscerocranium.","Most bones of the viscerocranium are paired, except for the mandible and vomer."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64121"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17945"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type